Tweet Text: @lowstrife Great point! I tend to bake this into my general EV calculation (my capital is tied up trading, that has some + EV from my trades, some - EV from risks like this), and then leverage is a multiplier on that. But making the risk explicit is important.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: There are many considerations here! And probably the ideal is a happy medium where exchanges offer >1x but <<100x leverage (which is a model many exchanges have moved to / are moving to). It's been nice to see that evolution. https://t.co/OprSI34rsJ
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: CON: great responsibility ... but, as we've seen from crypto's rampant liquidations, being allowed to use, for instance, 100x leverage is mostly bad for users who don't fully understand the risks they're taking. And exchanges lose customers who lose too many times.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: PRO: great power To the extent people are careful with their money and exchanges have reasonable margin rules, leverage really can represent a win-win. Users get to (hopefully!) make more $, exchanges get more volume -> revenue. Everyone wins!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: CON: getting rekt The price to pay for increased position sizing is that the exchange needs to liquidate you *before* you go bankrupt, which means that there's asymmetry introduced and people end up going bankrupt more often.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: PRO: scaling up If a great trader is suddenly allowed to put their trades on 2x as big, that's great for them! And really good risk managers can often afford to lever up even more, which is especially nice in a world with so many uses for capital (trading, yield, NFTs, etc.).
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: CON: price volatility That said, vs. a world with 0 leverage, there can be more volume in the real world (esp. vs. liquidity) which can lead to increased short-term volatility (not to mention the volatility introduced by liquidations, see below).
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: PRO: price discovery When people can put on larger positions, there's some extent to which people who feel stronger about prices have more impact on prices, which should lead prices to be more "correct" in certain senses, at least faster than otherwise.

Tweet Text: Not *un*important, mind you -- but less. And that's exactly what you expect of a more mature market where exchanges have been cracking down on super high leverage and more volume is driven by conservative institutions.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: So ... I really do feel like I don't know which direction things will go (I could believe more good news, I could believe some bad news, I could believe the market decides this was too much of a rally, etc.). But I do think liquidations are FINALLY starting to be less important. https://t.co/XDuhlGvX6N
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And the same is true for an upside move, roughly. Near a local max, there's always some chance for really old shorts to get wiped out since we're at prices they've never had to fend off -- but SO many of those have been liquidated on the way up already.

Tweet Text: Category 2 -- company X bought even more BTC -- is similar to company 40 doing it. MicroStrategy buying its 1st BTC was a BIG update. Them doing it for the 9th time? Not really any update at all! I would expect basically nothing about the price of BTC in the aftermath of that.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: But if they're the 40th company to announce it ... was that really unexpected based on the first 39? And they're not saying we're GONNA buy it -- they usually say they BOUGHT it. So this category *can* mean very little, depending on how unexpected a priori it should have been.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Like, before Elon started buying BTC, who knew if any non-finance firms would? But him doing it told the world: - maybe lots of others will follow - maybe Elon will do this many more times! And so that *can* represent big news.

Tweet Text: This is the typical pattern ‚Äî big effects DO arise, but if they‚Äôre predictable and consistent, they start happening sooner once everyone‚Äôs trading them, until they‚Äôre just totally arbed out. This is the paradigm I was used to when I started trading crypto.

Tweet Text: Let's say your capital would make .15%/day not tied up (from other trading, or yield farming, or whatever -- you have a better idea of this for your personal strategies). This makes your EV from trying to catch the wick .002 * 50% + .998 * -.15% = .05%/day -- a loss!

Tweet Text: A "typical" giant wick is for something like 50% edge. There are a few per day, on average, and a total of 1000 or so important / liquid markets -- so say that this happens on 1/500 of big markets per day. https://t.co/8SC8F76R2o

Tweet Text: This is powerful! It lets us maximize short-term EV almost all the time, assuming we are trying to maximize overall EV longer-term. And we *are* trying to do that -- @SBF_Alameda has talked extensively about the altruistic goals Alameda operates with.

Tweet Text: Markets rarely have sufficient liquidity such that our bet sizing is limited by our capital base -- much more often they're limited by how much we can put on without having giant price impact. The only things we can't do because of capital are like, buy half the ETH that exists.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Using the coin flip analogy, we've got $10000 instead of $10, and we can freely play the game as much as we want without having substantial risk of ruin. It's powerful, and increases our aggregate EV (per time unit since technically the EV is unbounded) since we can't go to $0. https://t.co/8wm0I7QBV5
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Why doesn't Alameda really have to do this? There are a few reasons. Day-to-day, the big one is that we have a ton of capital, and it's legit just quite rare that losing a potential bet would cause us real harm.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: In simple terms: how much value does your first $1m give you, as compared to your 10th? Your 100th? For most people who are just optimizing for their own happiness, utility is *definitely* sub-linear at some point -- $0 -> $1m is great, $99m -> $100m barely matters. https://t.co/JWO5ve0tju
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Really what's happening here is -- people's utility curves are not linear. (Something something Kelly Criterion, not re-opening that can of worms, suffice to say many people can rationally discount EV for risk, see below for why Alameda doesn't really.)
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: This is why, for instance, the insurance industry can succeed. Paying for insurance on your house is -EV -- on average, people pay more than the insurance company ever spends fixing houses. But for most, losing their house would be a giant setback. https://t.co/w0seYM7cEH
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Adjusting EV for risk is often a reasonable thing to do, especially when the risks you're taking are high relative to how much $ you have, or if losing would be especially bad for some reason. This is the source of advice like "don't bet more than you can afford to lose."
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Mistakes are natural in trading -- especially crypto trading where everything is so fucking weird. It's what you learn from your biggest mistakes that matters most, though -- and we've (thankfully) learned a lot. https://t.co/4Q8IyMcehg

Tweet Text: But from lemons we made plenty of lemonade. We changed our strategies a lot in the days/years following and have been able to do a lot better during high volatility ever since -- decreasing our median PNL but increasing our mean by a ton. And the E in EV only cares about means.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We had NO capacity to do the best trades on September 25, and that's the thing that hurt way more than getting liquidated. We'd gotten greedy for not enough edge which meant we couldn't maximize when it mattered most -- and we paid the price. https://t.co/8ORuM6dRY9
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And that meant halving our typical position sizes, and keeping a TON more spare capital around to put on giant futures positions when they got to these 10% discounts ... ... like they did again on March 12! And occasionally have for short periods in the time since.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: That means if a day like that happens > 1/200 of the time (which seemed likely, and is true), it's immediately good to optimize for those days instead. And that's disregarding that you might lose a lot to getting liquidated -- which, on the positions where it happened, we did :P
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: This was a crucial lesson for us! We hadn't really had to think hard about how valuable these giant move days are -- now we know how much we could make when they happen (200x the PNL of a then-normal day, conservatively). https://t.co/mskZubeWhW
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Most days? We're gonna make twice as much by doubling all our sizes. But on the rare days when the market *does* move 15%+? We're gonna have to mobilize additional collateral FAST, or we're gonna get fucked.

Tweet Text: What was sort of going on: we can always lever up and put on bigger positions than we are, the trade-off being higher probability of liquidation. So, maybe we're choosing between size X and 30% distance to liquidation vs. size 2X and 15% distance to liquidation.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: As a hedge, then, we were always long something else on margin -- often, for instance, BTC perps or futures. And back then, we sometimes played things a little fast and loose, collateral-wise. https://t.co/H4f5kNEBRh
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: So, what went wrong for us? I've mentioned we used to maintain delta-neutrality. Our capital base (at the time) was heavily concentrated in BTC. To get, for instance, spot USDT to trade with, we needed to sell some of that BTC, making us naturally short all the time.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: A 20% drop impacted the whole market, though -- liquidations happened everywhere, and various futures got to GIANT discounts as a result. Anyone with a ton of free capital could make a KILLING trading these -- buying the cheap futures vs. selling spot was even delta-neutral!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: The biggest source of liquidations back then was BitMEX BTC perps -- I used to spend a lot of time just sorta staring at that order book, moving our deltas in response to big changes -- to good effect! https://t.co/Cw0tK290Xy
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We've had smaller versions of the same thing unfold since -- we were plugged in to XRP enough to understand a) which news mattered b) how to bet on it c) when there would be momentum (basically, at recent highs/low, like for BTC at $20k). https://t.co/ta7urBlue0

Tweet Text: And we realized that our improved understanding of news would not only stop us from losing -- it could enable us to *win*. Tweet Text: So we spent a lot of time figuring out how to stay informed. We started spending more time on social media, we encouraged our whole team to urgently share big crypto news when they learn it, etc. And this did help; we started getting picked off to news less!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Well, it turns out you can't exactly solve this with just your trading bots -- if you wanna have good liquidity when flow is *not* informed, you need to lose to informed flow. The solution: be informed yourself.

Tweet Text: We always have to make these fast, crucial decisions -- it's what crypto trading is, really. And we got a lot better on March 12! It prepared us for trading a super-volatile election, trading the quick and huge $20k moves, trading XRP's 50% moves from the SEC, etc. etc.

Tweet Text: Seconds mattered here because *someone* was gonna close these spreads, *someone* was gonna make all this $ -- making it *us* was ALL we cared about, and it was so exciting to see our team figure all this out and gel in such a stressful situation.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We often had seconds to make huge decisions -- how big can our BitMEX perp position be? Big big should our OKEx/Huobi spread be? Where do we send our ETH? How much USDT can we deliver USD for right now? Where should we send out last available BTC collateral?

Tweet Text: So we needed our people to step up, and we had to rely on intuition. It was exciting! Many new things are, and there was so much uncertainty that it was kinda fun just to see how things would shake out.

Tweet Text: Figuring out that, yeah, there's $ to make in OKEx vs. Huobi -- but we need all our collateral on BitMEX because it's limited and BitMEX has the potential to print 50% good (and it did!) -- was ALL that mattered to maximize profit during this particular hour.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: It turned out that, no, probably I shouldn't have been! It was crucial to do one of two things: bet small s.t. your collateral was ROBUSTly safe, or restrict to just the very best trades. The latter was the way to go!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: But to do that for real size, you had to lever up and risk liquidation -- and how safe was that? This shit was all happening with BTC down 20% -- what if it fell another 20%? Am I comfortable risking a 30% loss if that happens just to lock in 10% of profit?
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: MAXIMIZE With everything in freefall, futures spreads got INSANE on March 12 -- many %s for many hours in delta-neutral spreads. OKEx and Huobi quarterlies -- close to identical products -- had a 10% spread at many points. So much $ to make, just buy one sell the other!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: But this highlights just how important it is to consider risk of ruin in putting spreads on. 20bp/day is NOT what we were making in EV on that futures spread -- if we had a 1% chance per day of liquidation and would then lose 10%, we were only making 10bp! Half the EV gone.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: ... well, on March 12, we would have been! And in some cases, we were. For a lot of our positions we *were* able to get more collateral in time, but not all of them -- we had to pick and choose which were the most valuable to salvage at the time. https://t.co/WfRUGzTrmh
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: So putting on a long spot / short futures position for 20bp/day isn't quite so simple -- for any real size, there's some chance of liquidation. Let's say we were 4x-levered or so, and a 25% move would cause us to get liquidated ...
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Doing that, though, requires posting collateral with the exchange. You can increase position size at the cost of more collateral or more risk to get liquidated, both of which are very real costs! Capital is useful for lots of stuff, and liquidation costs a LOT when it happens.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: ADJUST FOR RISK Alameda holds lots of positions -- some short-term when we expect some premium to revert fast, say, but some longer-term. For instance, if we sell a future expiring in a month 6% rich to make 20bp/day, we'll (often) gladly just hold for the whole month.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And we've learned our lesson here. Now, we track all kinds of possible signals for crypto which aren't *currently* useful but which *could* be -- even when we don't always have a great understanding for why. https://t.co/7Hc7UPHVZl https://t.co/zU7rSn2uwn
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: BTC lagging 30bp SPY moves by 30s is doable by hand, if need be. BTC lagging 5% SPY moves by 2s is NOT, and that's what started happening all at once -- adapting quickly matters to first order, but WAY more to second order, giving you outs to nail bigger follow-on changes.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: So we mobilized to get this into our models -- we had to, as we were getting picked off a ton to others who added it first (this is a huge problem when you're MMing for large size pretty tight, which we were and are). And thank god, because March 12 hit and this became critical.

Tweet Text: The rest of the world is missing out on something for being so distrustful of USDT, I think -- but if no one else wants to collect this premium consistently, I guess we'll have to suck it up. https://t.co/7wKSzKeHoo
Media Alt Text: helping schitts creek GIF by CBC
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Having done so much of this and worked so closely with their team is why we trust USDT much more than the rest of crypto twitter seems to at times :P Having done big creations when USDT > 1 and big redemptions when it's < 1 will do that -- and that's been a powerful tool.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And, as we've been noting recently on Twitter, we do these! A lot! And this is win-win -- obviously we're making money to it because we can, e.g., be selling above where we create, but we're also bringing the price in line so that when aggro buyers come in, it sticks close to $1.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: That's, for instance, a big part of the reason the price came back in line while I was writing this tweet :P when it diverges from $1 we can pretty safely put on big bets because, well, we *do* have the necessary setup to do large creations and redemptions when we want to.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And when USDT gets above $1? A sophisticated firm like Alameda with great setups on all the exchanges and bots to execute more than one leg at a time is gonna want to sell! And we do -- a LOT.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Other stablecoins like USDC don't have anywhere near as volatile premia -- that's because the creation/redemption process is more involved for USDT, and fewer firms can actually do it. This is why, as I noted above, many who want it are going to markets and not creating.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Man, USDT fell back to $1 (in the BTC/USDT markets) as I was typing those previous tweets :P It really does trade a ton, and not especially efficiently on a second-to-second timescale. https://t.co/8nzzPbylk8
Media Alt Text: Patrick's Grumpy Roller Coaster Ride GIF
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: (They're trying to get it for the reasons noted in the article, as well as maybe some other idiosyncratic ones pending market conditions -- distrust in local currency/banks, collateral, access to the super liquid USDT markets chief among them.)
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And note, *these* are the best markets to use to determine where USDT is trading -- the combo of BTC/USDT and BTC/USD markets, e.g., are WAY more liquid than any exchange's USDT/USD market, so the prices from these (even though it's a two-leg trade) matter way more.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: The premium with which USDT trades to $1 is pretty volatile as a result -- as I type this, the average BTC/USDT market (as compared to BTC/USD) is trading about 15bp lower, implying USDT = $1.0015 or so. And that's all from people AGGRESSIVELY selling BTC vs. USDT to get USDT.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: BTW, to connect some dots here -- a lot of the people seeking access to a coin like USDT *aren't* doing so via creation. They're often doing so via just sorta buying it in the markets -- and they're buying a LOT, and REALLY aggressively.

Tweet Text: And they get liquidated less, too -- so these buys weren't apt to get undone as easily as 100x levered-long Binance perps would on the first draw-down. All this is to say: this rally was driven by more "organic" buying, in both spot and derivatives markets.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: A big difference? These products (spot and the OK/HB quarterlies) tend to have way less leverage (possible or realized, as the case may be) -- the positions get held for more time, and buyers in them tend to indicate "I'm buying to hold" more than "I'm buying to scalp."
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And the returns column indicates that the premium on those quarterlies went up a TON more than other products' did -- these were AGGRESSIVE buyers, and they were buying a ton. This was the pattern for most of these inflows -- less BitMEX/Binance perps, more quarterlies/spot.

Tweet Text: Only seeing one side of a trader‚Äôs arbitrage can paint a pretty wrong picture about what the trader is up to, and looking only at a fraction of their trades is going to do just that. Be wary of making assumptions like this!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We use all kinds of arbitrage-based strategies like this (some literal arbitrages, some things like ‚Äúbuy on Binance, send to Uniswap to sell,‚Äù some that involve holding deltas a bit longer but eventually closing, some hedged futures vs. spot spreads, etc.).
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Indeed, great trading opportunities often arise on Uniswap -- coins get out of line there vs. other platforms, and if AAVE is rich on Uniswap vs. e.g. Binance (this happens all the time), we‚Äôre going to sell on Uniswap and buy on Binance -- who wouldn‚Äôt?
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: But it isn‚Äôt! And while it is true that we have net sold AAVE on Uniswap, it turns out that we‚Äôve actually net *bought* AAVE overall over the same time periods. Looking at only one (or a few) of many platforms does not tell the whole story about what we (or anyone) are doing.

Tweet Text: So, if this market does end up existing, I think it will be more important than almost ever to questions our own assumptions really aggressively -- selection bias can be a killer. (And note: I really *don‚Äôt* have a clue what my fair is for this right how, need to think on it.)
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We‚Äôve found that rarely to be the case for, e.g., BTC -- but sometimes to be the case for big shitcoin trades. Selection bias will tend to be a bigger factor the more idiosyncratic the trade is, and the more sorts of things your counterparty could know that you don‚Äôt.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Mainly how drastically fairs change when you make small perturbations about starting assumptions, and just how uncertain those assumptions are for the whole world right now. Information is power here, and a big order implies information.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: On some level, these are the kinds of considerations I have all the time when thinking about all kinds of trades -- after all, someone‚Äôs always on the other side of all my trades, and each time I make a trade I‚Äôm choosing to trust my info over theirs. What‚Äôs different here?
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: (Or, it can also imply that they‚Äôre SUPER risk-averse, for some reason, and are willing to pay for insurance -- if I can become convinced of this, or just that they‚Äôre wrong, a trade COULD happen in this case, and I think buying insurance is the main way this market will exist.)
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Either way, I definitely have to consider that this other party has information I don‚Äôt of some nature -- and that‚Äôs terrifying, so I‚Äôm going to have to strongly think about my own information, and likely update my fair -- maybe by a lot! And that might kill the trade.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And if they have that much money on OKEx, should I be updating toward their opinion? It might imply some probability of them having ties to OKEx in a way where I should maybe assume they know something I don‚Äôt, sometimes. Or even that they learned public info faster than I did.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Do they actually have marginal return on capital -- for any exchange vs. just for OKEx -- high enough to justify that? Probably impossible, even if trading on OKEx totally dries up. That HAS to imply they‚Äôre pricing risk of ruin very, very high.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: In particular, I think there‚Äôs REALLY intense selection bias in a market like this one -- if my starting fair discount is 5% and someone offers me their entire $50m holdings for a 20% discount, I HAVE to wonder why they‚Äôre willing to do that.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And that‚Äôs just one part of the story, anyway -- I think various market conditions should have WAY outsized impact in a situation like this one, and fairs should be fairly quickly abandoned / updated as new information arises.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Maybe I have some (perceived) information about what‚Äôs actually going on with the CEO, and I therefore think that it‚Äôs HIGHLY unlikely that the funds actually not get recovered -- my fair discount should then start a LOT lower (much closer to 2.5%). I‚Äôm not sure which is better!
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: This would lead to a discount of .2 * .75 = 15% from this factor, plus .8 * 2.5% = 2% for capital cost the rest of the time. That leads to an overall fair discount of 17% -- using a TON of assumptions that could be really off.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: It does strike me as not especially likely that cases where funds cannot be recovered, on average, lead to 100% of funds not being able to be recovered -- let‚Äôs call it an average of 75% of funds that never get recovered whenever this occurs.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Is it really plausible that this probability is as high as 20%? Maybe! I don‚Äôt claim to be an expert on any of the relevant factors. So let‚Äôs call it 20%, again for the sake of continuing (I‚Äôm not claiming to believe that‚Äôs the real probability, could be way less or way more).
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: OKEx, of course, claims 100%. Again, everyone has their own opinion here about what sorts of factors that might render the funds impossible to salvage could be at play and how likely they are -- China clamping down, CEO being MIA forever, etc. And this probability is critical.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Cool -- so if we know ~the funds are safe~ then maybe about a 2.5% discount is fair, assuming some things about timeline and my marginal returns. What are the chances that the funds are actually safe?
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: That‚Äôd mean I expect my funds to be locked up for, on average, .02 * 1 + .02 * 2 + ‚Ä¶ + .02 * 30 + .1 * 60 + .1 * 90 + .1 * 120 + .1 * 150 = 51.3 days. Since the marginal capital cost is 5bp/day, that should cost me about 2.5%.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Let‚Äôs just pick a distribution for the sake of continuing -- maybe I believe that there‚Äôs a 2% chance that the funds unlock each day for the next month, and then a 10% chance that they unlock at the end of each of the following four months.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: (That‚Äôs true for pricing almost any asset over any time period, though, which is the basis of the existence of trading :D)

Tweet Text: Next, you need to build a probability distribution for when the funds get unlocked (let‚Äôs pretend that all the funds get unlocked all at once, for simplicity). Tons of assumptions and different sets of info come into play in divining this, and everyone‚Äôs answer will vary.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: At least not on average -- presumably the capital being there implies you‚Äôd usually keep some capital there, which means that you‚Äôre getting some utility from having it there. So, assuming that OKEx maintains trading at close to typical volume, call this 5bp/day.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: To determine what the cost of the capital is short-term, you first need to determine what the marginal return on capital you could move freely is vs. capital that you can only use on OKEx. Honestly, for the capital you were *already holding* on OKEx, this shouldn‚Äôt be HUGE.

Tweet Text: There‚Äôs also a lot of math in the trading side -- I skimmed over the research process in how we develop strategies (hey, that‚Äôs the other word in our name), but we spend a ton of time on it, and we‚Äôd be screwed without it.

Tweet Text: (By which I mean: there‚Äôs a million buttons we‚Äôre pushing all the time and they have lots of sometimes hard-to-predict effects, and they interact with each other.)

Tweet Text: I‚Äôd summarize the differences between this and our investing as: different timescales (shorter trades + we also have less time to think), a little more agnostic about ‚Äúwhat we‚Äôre doing‚Äù (sometimes we trust data over e.g. the macro elements of a coin), and more game-like.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: On a high level, that‚Äôs kind of it -- we learn about the markets, we come up with strategies, we test them, we run them, we think about how risky they are, we count our money. The specifics can get gnarly and really challenging (and fun!), but that‚Äôs the gist.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: There‚Äôs a ton going on here, and we often have to make risk adjustment decisions in seconds -- it‚Äôs another reason that humans are so important, and it‚Äôs an added layer when we‚Äôre considering each and every one of our strategies.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Some risks: platforms defaulting, transfers failing, a position getting liquidated before we can exit, entering into an unhedged but risky position that could go against us, a tech disaster causing us to lose a lot, etc. etc. etc.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Broadly, we weigh how valuable a given action is vs. how much potential downside that action has (and how likely the downside is), and then if it meets so bar we do the action. And there are all kinds of risks, some of which are really hard to evaluate.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Another wrinkle to this game is *risk* -- how do we think about risk? What if the money goes somewhere dangerous?
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: (Our capital base also is not fixed -- many platforms offer leverage and loans and whatnot now, and so you can scale up your capital base if you can accept more risk -- we think about this all the time!)

Tweet Text: Now, the strategies are not *actually* that independent -- often they‚Äôre drawing from the same pools of capital, and often their returns are quite correlated. But this model of how our day-to-day works is basically right.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: The same is broadly true for yield farming: at any point, there‚Äôs a fixed return on capital for each platform, and we need to decide what to allocate where. Yields can change quickly, of course, but that‚Äôs true for the returns from any strategy, so this is basically the same.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: (That‚Äôs how I‚Äôd characterize our manual trading, too -- we leave a ton of collateral on the derivatives platforms, for instance, so we as human traders can decide to put on a huge position if we ever want to.)
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Some of our strategies are more passive, most of the time, and sort of amount to ‚Äúleave a bunch of money sitting on some exchange and wait for the 1% of times it‚Äôs best to enter a huge position.‚Äù Estimating how good and rare those opportunities are dictates how much to allocate.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: To some extent, given a set of lots of these strategies, what our day-to-day trading is can be described as: we have some capital base we can deploy however we want -- how do we decide where to put it? This optimization problem is at the core of what we always do.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: We run studies to determine what sets of inputs give us reliably good information, test the strategies to make sure the liquidity is real, and then scale up. It‚Äôs really just the scientific method, applied to a specific set of market games. And that gives us strategies.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And what kind of inputs do we use? Basically, anything systematic which we can ingest is fair game -- order book data, trade data, blockchain data, yield data, data from non-crypto markets (SPX, etc.), open interest data, etc. etc. etc.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: And often when markets are quite volatile, there will be a ton of manual intervention and pushing of knows that put on positions we as humans recognize as good -- this is usually quite fast, and based on the intuition and fast thinking which makes it hard to automate me away.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Some of our strategies are longer-term -- maybe we‚Äôll have some automated signal which suggests coin X will go up over the next day, so we‚Äôll hold the position for a day. Usually it‚Äôs something a bit shorter, but we‚Äôll follow the money anywhere.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Our trading is not monolithic, and so there aren‚Äôt that many highly-specific claims I can make which apply to all of it. Some of our strategies involve doing thousands of trades back and forth, not holding much of a position ever.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: The gist of all of our activities? Follow the money. If there‚Äôs money somewhere, we want to be there. And so we devote a lot of time and energy to 1) figuring out where the money is 2) getting there.

Tweet Text: How does the PNL graph get generated? Basically, we ascribe some set of trades that we did as having happened due to the despos changes.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: When we change the DELTA_ALL despos, that affects *all* our quotes (except something like USDT/USD which doesn't really have BTC exposure). This is something we touch manually quite often, since we really often want to ‚Äúbuy crypto‚Äù or ‚Äúsell crypto.‚Äù
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: DELTA_ALL is our measure of ‚Äúoverall crypto exposure.‚Äù The gist of it is: using recent historical correlation (basically), we give each coin a beta to BTC, then add that up for every coin we trade, and that‚Äôs our DELTA_ALL (so named because it‚Äôs the delta of all our positions).
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: A despos can be set for anything -- something specific like ‚ÄúBTC 0626 quarterlies on FTX,‚Äù something broader like ‚Äúall BTC perpetuals,‚Äù and something even broader like ‚Äúall BTC products.‚Äù The one here, though, is the broadest that any our systems support -- DELTA_ALL.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Many different sources can contribute desposes to the bots -- many are automated, but the ‚Äúpointer desposes‚Äù (the ones set in pointer) are 100% manual and are how our traders enact their desires to buy or sell a given product or set of products.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: Next, pointer: this is the name of our internal trading system. It‚Äôs where we monitor our bots‚Äô trades, see/edit parameters, see markets, and can execute manual trades as well. One set of parameters we update all the time are the pointer desposes.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.

Tweet Text: First, despos: this is our internal shorthand for ‚Äúdesired position,‚Äù and is something we use to encourage our bots to buy or sell. If we increase our desired position, our bots will become more set up to buy (fading our quotes up), and vice-versa.
Original Author Description (Bio): Former CEO + crypto quant trader @ https://t.co/HgMj6usiBe. Sports were too hard so I did math instead. Not investment advice.
